&gt; possible for people to be dismissive, not only of art, philosophy and
&gt; religion, but of the requirements and limitations of true scientific
&gt; research. They eviscerate the human spirit, by insisting that, in the
&gt; last analysis, everything is random and meaningless. Conversely, they
&gt; justify true fascism (&quot;survival of the fittest&quot;), and all the horrors
&gt; of eugenics, abortions and euthanasia.
">

At the risk of riding my hobbyhorse one time too many into battle, is
there a creationist alive who notes the teensy-tiny contradiction
between &quot;Darwinism insists that everything is random and meaningless&quot;
and &quot;Darwinism justifies true fascism, etc.?&quot;  If everything is random
and meaningless, there are no justifications for anything.  If
everything is &quot;randomly contrived,&quot; then what is &quot;survival of the
fittest&quot; except an empty phrase without enough content to base a
political ideology on?  But then, it seems to me that there is at
least some tension between the author's assertion that Darwin (like
Marx and Freud) was a &quot;Victorian determinist,&quot; and his horror at the
&quot;randomness&quot; of evolutionary theory.

The author states that he has read Darwin.  Perhaps this is even true,
although nothing Darwin says seems to have much shaped his views of
Darwin's ideas.  Certainly he has not seemed to grasp another point:
that evolutionary theory is not religion, nor even an ideology like
Marxism, such that it depends on the authority and genius of its
original author, so that all issues in the field can be settled by an
appeal to the prophet and his writings.  He does not, at least in
this short column, show any interest in any evolutionary theorist
since Darwin.

I have this sneaking suspicion (perhaps entirely unjustified) that to
the author, the &quot;true limitations of scientific research&quot; are that
science cannot possibly discover anything he'd really rather not know,
nor can its results contradict anything he'd prefer to believe.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Moral relativism could not stand, except on a Darwinist base, and
&gt; reason itself is rendered defenceless, by the notion that all nature
&gt; was randomly contrived.
">

It seems to me that moral relativism could stand quite well on a
creationist base: assume (as ID permits) that the Creator simply
hasn't bothered to create an objective, absolute moral code and that
we're pretty much on our own trying to figure out right from wrong.
OTOH, the Panda's Thumb features an article by Hector Avalos arguing
that  creationism specifically implies moral relativism: &lt;http://
www.talkreason.org/articles/Genocide.cfm#christ &gt;.  Since evolutionary
theory does not, in fact, hold that &quot;all nature was randomly
contrived,&quot; but implies that our minds were shaped by the need to
actually represent nature in a consistently useful manner, ISTM that
David Warren is also wrong that &quot;reason itself is rendered
defenceless&quot; by &quot;Darwinism.&quot;

